 :tx/rationale "C9-OPTION-ANALYSIS: Scoring 5 options for observation retrieval ergonomics. The test: can I answer 'what are the top audit findings?' in one command? OPTION A (braid recall): New command, context-aware, auto-groups by concept. Score: 8/10. Pro: purpose-built for the exact use case. Con: new command = new code surface, duplicates query logic, doesn't compose with existing commands. New concept to learn. OPTION B (improve braid seed): Make seed work mid-session with better observation surfacing. Score: 5/10. Pro: reuses existing infrastructure. Con: seed is designed for session-start budget-constrained injection, not mid-session exploration. Overloading its purpose violates single-responsibility. OPTION C (improve braid query): Add shorthand observation queries. Score: 6/10. Pro: extends existing query command, composable. Con: query is already complex (Datalog + entity + attribute modes), adding observation-specific shortcuts is a leaky abstraction. OPTION D (improve braid status --verbose): Score: 4/10. Status is a dashboard, not an exploration tool. Making it show 20 observation bodies makes it too long. Wrong tool for the job. OPTION E (add --list --search --show to braid observe): Score: 9/10. This is the unix answer. braid observe creates observations. braid observe --list shows them. braid observe --search 'AUDIT' finds them. braid observe --show <id> displays one. Exactly mirrors braid task {list,search,show}. Zero new concepts. Composes with existing patterns. The implementation is trivial: same pattern as task.rs search/list/show but over :exploration/body entities. Observation is already the noun. List/search/show are already the verbs the agent knows from task management. EVIDENCE: I already successfully used 'braid task search AUDIT' to find audit tasks. If 'braid observe --search AUDIT' existed, I would have used it to find observations instead of falling back to markdown files. The failure mode was: the search verb existed for tasks but not for observations. WINNER: Option E. Add --list, --search, --show to braid observe."
